<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>SINGLE SPEED REAR AXLE: INTERNATIONAL - PINION POSITION - Pinion Position</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="6">
        <title>Pinion Position</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To establish the correct nominal dimension by using a pinion setting gauge, install pinion
                gear and cage assembly to housing without shims. Refer to the
                <hotlnk document="s14008t_30.xml" xrefid="hl1400805">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>, for proper fastener torque.
                Failure to tighten properly may result in incorrect gear adjustment.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Attach the step plate clamp assembly to the carrier mounting flange. Locate step plate clamp
                screw over center of pinion gear. Install step plate under clamp screw and tighten to hold step plate
                securely in position (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400854">Figure 54</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400854" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400854" filename="../figg14/G1400854.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 54. Step Plate Secure In Position</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Be sure lugs on bottom of step plate straddle the bearing staking indentations on end of
                        pinion, or false reading may occur. Also, make sure differential side bearing bores are clean
                        and free of nicks.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove any burrs and wipe clean differential bearing bore I.D.s. Turn micrometer 90 degrees
                to step plate.
            </para>
            <para>Install assembled pinion setting gauge into bearing bores of carrier housing. Adjust micrometer so it
                is directly over end of step plate. Run the micrometer thimble down to measure the distance between the
                center of the ring gear and the step plate (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400855">Figure 55</hotlnk>).
                <emph type="bold">Make a note of this dimension.</emph>
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400855" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400855" filename="../figg14/G1400855.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 55. Measure With Micrometer</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Because the step plate must be taken into consideration, the thickness of the step plate [.400
                        inch (10.16 mm) ] needs to be added to the measured value for the correct micrometer distance.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">On the machined end of each pinion gear is etched either a plus (+) number, a minus (-)
                number or a zero (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400856">Figure 56</hotlnk>). This number represents the amount in thousandths of an
                inch (.001) to be added (+) or subtracted (-) from the nominal dimension for the best running position
                for that particular gear set.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400856" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400856" filename="../figg14/G1400856.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 56. Pinion Etch</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>EXAMPLE: If pinion is etched +3, the required mounting distance is more than nominal by .003 inch
                (.076 mm). This means the pinion would require .003 inch (.076 mm) thicker shim between pinion bearing
                cage assembly and carrier housing than a pinion etched with "0."
            </para>
        </step1>
        <para>If the pinion is marked -3, the shim required between pinion bearing cage assembly and carrier housing
            would be .003 inch (.076 mm) thinner than if pinion was etched "0."
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The following two examples illustrate how proper running position is achieved by computing
                dimensions you have obtained.
            </para>
        </step1>
