        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>If exact shim measurement cannot be achieved, use available shims to approximate correct pinion
                    position.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Position shims on carrier housing so oil return holes align properly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400857">Figure 57</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400857" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400857" filename="../figg14/G1400857.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 57. Position Shims On Housing</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Be certain mounting surfaces and shims are free of dirt and nicks or leaks may occur and
                        pinion position can be affected.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install pinion and pinion cage assembly into carrier (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400858">Figure 58</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400858" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400858" filename="../figg14/G1400858.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 58. Install Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Studs can be used to assist in alignment.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Tighten pinion cage to carrier bolts. Refer to the
                <hotlnk document="s14008t_30.xml" xrefid="hl1400805">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>, for proper fastener torque (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400859">Figure 59</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400859" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400859" filename="../figg14/G1400859.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 59. Tighten Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">An alternative to using the pinion setting gauges is to use the following procedure.</para>
        </step1>
        <para>Use a micrometer to measure thickness of old pinion shims. Measure each shim separately and add together
            to get total thickness of original build-up.
        </para>
    </svcproc>
